column168: CONCERNED CITIZEN CONTACTED ILLINOIS CENTRAL RAILROAD STATING THAT VAPOR WAS COMMING FROM THE TOP OF TANK CAR RCRX1322 IN ONE OF OUR TRAINS.  OUR RECORDS SHOWED THIS CAR IN THE CONSIST OF SOUTHBOUND TRAIN CRGE06.  CREW WAS RADIOED TO STOP TRAIN AT FLORA, MS FOR INSPECTION.  VISUAL INSPECTION OF TRAIN CONFIRMED CITIZENS REPORT AND CAR WAS SET OUT ON SIDE TRACK.  ILLINOIS CENTRAL HAZ MAT TECHNICIAN, FLORA POLICE, SHERIFF DEPT AND FERGUSON HARBOR ENVIRONMENTAL ALL CALLED TO THE SCENE. IC HAZ MAT TECHNICIAN FOUND THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK TO BE THE DIP TUBE FLANGE.  THREE OF THE FOUR BOLTS THAT HOLD THE FLANGE TIGHT WERE NOT SECURED AND THE FOURTH BOLT WAS SIMPLY NOT APPLIED AND LEFT ON TOP OF THE FLANGE.  HE TIGHTENED THE THREE BOLTS AND APPLIED THE FOURTH AND TIGHTENED. FERGUSON HARBOR APPLIED AN AGRICULTURAL LIME SOLUTION TO THE TOP AND SIDES OF THE TANK CAR TO NEUTRALIZE AY PRODUCT THAT MAY HAVE BEEN IN THOSE AREAS.  TAN CAR RCRX 1322 WAS THEN RELEASED BACK  TO TRANSPORTATION AND ON TO DESTINATION.

WHILE TRAILER 6865 WAS BEING LOADED THE SHIPPER NOTICED PRODUCT LEAKING THROUGH THE SKIN.  THE SHIPPER STOPPED LOADING AND STARTED UNLOADING THE TRAILER BACK INTO THEIR VESSEL.  THE SHIPPER CONTAINED THE LEAK INTO BUCKETS.  THIS IS VIRTUALLY IMPOSSIBLE TO DETECT WITHOUT A PRESSURE TEST ON THE VESSEL.  A STRESS IN THE METAL WAS UNDETECTED UNTIL PRODUCT WAS PUT IN THE TRAILER.

column168: BLEACH PRODUCT WAS LOADING SLOWLY.  THE DRIVER WENT TO INVESTIGATE, AND RETURNED TO FIND THE PRODUCT RUNNING OUT THE DOME LID.  THE VALVE WAS TURNED OFF.  CLEAN UP WAS STARTED BY PLANT PERSONNEL.  THE PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED ON SITE IN SECONDARY CONTAINMENT.  75 GALLONS OF PEROXIDE WAS USED TO NEUTRALIZE THE SPILL THAT MIXED WITH ALUMINUM SULFATE SOLUTION.  HYPOCHORUS ACID VAPOR WAS RELEASED AND PICKED UP BY PLANT SENSORS.  CONTRA COSTA FIRE RESPONDED TO THE ALARM.  CCFD WAS INFORMED THAT THE IN HOUSE HAZMAT TEAM HAD THE SITUATION UNDER CONTROL. THE LEFT AND THE CLEAN UP WAS FINISHED AT ABOUT 6AM.  THE BYPRODUCT WAS THEN USED  IN PROCESS, SO NO WASTE WAS GENERATED.  RECOMMEND MOVING NON COMPATIBLE PRODUCT LOADING OUT OF THE SAME AREA TO LOAD WITH A COMPATIBLE PRODUCT, THAT BEING TO LOAD AT THE CAUSTIC LOAD RACK.  ANY SUBSEQUENT NEUTRALIZATION MATERIALS, PERSONNEL SUITING UP IN LEVEL B FOR CLEAN UP AND REDUCE COST SPILL.  DRIVER WAS SENT TO MEDICAL CLINIC FOR POST DRUG TESTING AND WAS PLACED O 3 DAY SUSPENSION WITH OU PAY FOR VIOLATING LOADING SOP THAT COMPANY HAS ESTABLISHED. THIS DOCUMENT IS NUMBER 9801E TO GO WITH THE INCIDENT REPORT NUMBER AS A CORRELATION.

column168: ILLINOIS CENTRAL NETWORK OPERATIONS WAS CALLED BY CHEMTREC TO ALERT US OF A CALL THEY HAD RECEIVED FROM  A LT. SHANNON OF THE UNION CITY POLICE DEPARTMENT.  LT. SHANNON ADVISED CHEMTREC THAT TWO TANK CARS AT THE CARBONIC INDUSTRIES HAVE BEEN VENTING FOR 1 & 1/2 HOURS.  THEY ARE DISTURBING LOCAL RESIDENTS AND HE WOULD LIKE SOMETHING DONE WITH THEM.  CHEMTREC BRIEFED LT. SHANNON ON THE VENTING PROCESS OF TANK CARS.  LT. SHANNON ADVISED THAT HE DID NOT THINK THAT THIS WAS NORMAL VENTING.  LT. SHANNON WAS UNABLE TO GIVE CHEMTREC TANK CAR NUMBER OF SHIPPER/CONSIGNEE INFORMATION. ILLINOIS CENTRAL DISPATCHED A TRAINMASTER TO THE SCENE TO INVESTIGATE.  TRAINMASTER FOUND ONE TANK CAR VENTING AT THE CARBONIC INDUSTRIES CALLED TRAINMASTER AND AFTER A BRIEF CONVERSATION SAID THEY ARE SENDING SOMEONE TO LOOK AT CAR.  DON STEVENS, FACILITY MANAGER FOR CARBONIC ARRIVED AT THE SCENE AND BLED THE PRESSURE OFF THE CAR.  HE FOUND THE FRANGIBLE DISC HAD RUPTURED.  HE REPLACED THE DISC AND SECURED THE CAR.  TANK CAR GATX 21612 REMAINED AT THE CARBONIC INDUSTRIES, UNION CITY FACILITY FOR OFF LOADING.

column62: Defective Component or Device; Corrosion - Exterior
column168: DRIVER WAS UNLOADING WHEN HE NOTICED  A DROP OF LIQUID FALL FROM THE BACK OF THE EXTERNAL VALVE HOUSING.  HE PLACED A BUCKET UNDER THE VALVE.  WHEN THE DRIP TURNED INTO A STREAM THE DRIVER CLOSED THE VALVES AND STOPED THE DELIVERY.  HE HAD ABOUT A QUART OF CAUSTITC IN THE BUCKET.  INSPECTION OF THE VALVE REVEALED A HOLE IN THE WELD.

AFTER DRIVER RECEIVED OK TO UNLOAD, HE STARTED TO TRANSFER PRODUCT FROM CARGO TANK TO STORAGE TANK VIA HIS TRACTOR PUMP.  HE OPENED ALL VALVES AND ENGAGED PUMP. PRESSURE DEVELOPED IN LINE AND CAUSED HOSE TO BURST.  IT WAS DETERMINED THEIR LINE WAS PLUGGED.  CONSIGNEE DIRECTED HOSES TO STORAGE TANKER.  CONSIGNEE INFORMED DRIVER THEY WOULD CLEAN AREA AFTER UNIT WAS DONE UNLOADING.  THEY HAD CONTAINED SPILL AND SPREAD OIL DRY AND WILL PUT INTO DRUM.

A SKID FELL OFF THE FORKLIFT CAUSING A 16 GALLON DRUM LID TO POP OFF.  THE SPILL HAPPENED IN THE WAREHOUSE (CONCRETE SECONDARY CONTAINMENT) .  SPILL WAS RECOVERED WITH ABSORBANT AND DRUMMED FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.
DRIVER WAS PUMPING MATERIAL FROM TANK TRUCK TO PER.  STORAGE TANK AND SPOTTED AND SPOTTED A PIN HOLE IN THE HOSE.  SPILL WAS CLEANED UP WITH ABSORBENT PADS AND DRUMMED UP FOR PROPPER DISPOSAL.

WHILE DRIVER WAS LOADING A 30 GALLON DRUM OF WASTE ONTO SKID TRUCK #5143.  HE TIPPED THE DRUM SIDEWAYS AND MATERIAL LEAKED FROM A PIN HOLE IN THE SIDE. SPILL CLEANED UP WITH ABSORBENT AND DRUMMED UP FOR DISPOSITION

WHEN WAREHOUSE MAN OPENED UP A 350 GALLON TOTE OF MATERIAL.  THE WAREHOUSE MAN REPORTED THAT THE MATERIAL SHOT OUT OF THE TOTE DUE TO PRESSURE IN THE TOTE.  THE MATERIAL SPILLED ONTO THE CONCRETE CONTAINMENT FLOOR.  MATERIAL WAS RECOVERED WITH ABSORBENT PADS AND DRUMMED UP FOR PROPER DISPOSAL AT SAFETY - KLEEN IN   , CA

DOCK WORKER WAS MOVING DRUM WITH FORK LIFT PUNCTURED BOTTOM OF DRUM. I TIPPED DRUM ON ITS SIDE TO STOP LEAK.  I EVACUATED IMMEDIATE AREA AND CALLED CHEMTRAC.  CHEMTRAC SAID IT WAS A VERY CORROSIVE SUBSTANCE AND NEEDED GOGGLES , APRON, GLOVES TO PUT IN A CONTAINER DRUM.  CHEMTRAC ALSO TALKED TO OAKITE PRODUCTS AND THEY WANT THE DRUM TAKEN BACK TO THEM.

WHILE UNLOADING DRUMS WITH A FORKLIFT ATTACHMENT PART OF THE ATTACHMENT STRUCK THE DRUM AND PUNCTURED IT CAUSING A SMALL MINIMAL LEAK. OPERATOR RE-INSTRUCTED AS TO PROPER USE OF THIS ATTACHMENT TO PREVENT FUTURE INSTANCES

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: DRUM WAS LOADED ON TOP OF CARDBOARD. CARDBOARD WAS ON TOP OF A PIECE OF WOOD WITH A NAIL/PROTRUSION. THIS PUNCTURED THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM.

DOCK WORKER WAS UNLOADING TRAILER. TEXO DRUM WAS NEXT TO BE TAKEN OFF. WORKER PLACED DRUM DOLLY ON SIDE AND TILTED BACK. PRODUCT STARTED LEAKING FROM LIDS ON BARREL. WORKED SAT DRUM BACK DOWN & NOTIFIED DISPATCH. CHEM TREC & SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED OF PROBLEM.
SHIPMENT WAS ON ENROUTE TRLR TO XCJ TERMINAL. LOOKS LIKE FIBRE DRUM WAS HIT WITH A PALLET CAUSING LEAK. SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED FOR MSDS & DISPOSITION.
column172: Fiber drum, cont1 for solids, cont2 for liquids

column168: DSR WAS BREAKING A TRAILER. TRIED TO MOVE DRUMS WITH FORK LIFT AND PUNCTURED DRUM. DSR HAD AN INCIDENT REPORT WRITTEN AND SENT TO HIS FILE.

column42: PETROLEUM DISTILLATES, N.O.S. OR PETROLEUM PRODUCTS, N.O.S.
column168: OPENED TRAILER DOOR FOR UNLOADING AT TERMINAL. NOTICE STRONG ODOR FROM 2 TOES ON TAIL OF TRAILER, NOTICED PRODUCT LEAKING FROM TOP DOWN THE SIDES ONTO THE TRAILER FLOOR. AT THAT POINT WE CONTACTED PAT LIGHT FOR DISPOSAL. FROM IDENTICAL SPILL, JUST A MONTH EARLIER THE PAPERWORK WAS COMPLETED. WE DETERMINED THE SPILL WAS FROM A LOOSE LID ON THE TOTE.

AT TIME OF LOADING THE DRUM WAS REMOVED FROM THE SMALL SKID TO AVOID THE DRUM FROM TURNING OVER IN TRANSIT. WHILE REMOVING FROM THE SKID I WOULD SAY THAT THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM HIT THE CORNER OF THE SKID CAUSING THE PIN HOLE IN DRUM. DUNNAGE WAS PLACED UNDER THE DRUM SO VERY LITTLE MATERIAL CAME OUT. WHEN THE TRAILER WAS OPENED IN PARKERSBURG A CLEAN UP CREW WAS CALLED IN TO HANDLE THE CLEANUP.

column42: COMPOUND, CLEANING, LIQUID (CONTAINING PHOSPHORIC ACID, ACETIC ACID, SODIUM HYDROXIDE OR POTASSIUM HYDROXIDE)
column62: Dropped; Improper Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing; Too Much Weight on Package
column168: DOCK WORKER OPENED DOOR AND SAW A LEAKING CASE CRUSHED BETWEEN 2 SKIDS, REST OF ORDER WAS ON A SKID DOUBLE STACKED, THE CASE THAT WAS DAMAGED HAD FALLEN OFF THE SKID AND WAS LODGED BETWEEN 2 SKIDS ON THE FLOOR. THE BOUNCING OF THE TRAILER CRUSHED THE CASE BETWEEN THE TWO SKIDS CAUSING IT TO LEAK! HAZARDOUS MATERIAL SHOULD NEVER BE STACKED IN A TRAILER. IT SHOULD HAVE BEEN PACKED AND PROPERLY BLOCKED ON THE FLOOR! THE CASE ITSELF WAS PACKED BY THE SHIPPER OK! THE GALLON JUG WOULD HAVE NEVER LEAKED IF IT WASN'T CRUSHED! DOCK WORKER WROTE UP DAMAGED AN, AND IT WAS PUT IN A RECOVERY DRUM SO NO MORE LEAKAGE WILL OCCUR! THERE WAS NOT MUCH LEAKAGE ON FLOOR, MAINLY CASE WAS SOAKED! NO OTHER DAMAGES TO ANY OTHER FREIGHT.

DRUM STRUCK BY FORKLIFT, DRUM  PLACED ON SIDE, SPILL WAS CLEANED AND PLACED IN SALVAGE DRUM, SENT ONTO DESTINATION.
DUE TO VIBRATION IN TRANSIT, PAILS LEAKED SMALL AMOUNT. THE SPILL WAS CLEANED AND LIDS TIGHTENED, SHIPMENT SENT ONTO DESTINATION.

column172: Plastic jug, capacity more than 2 gallons and less than 5 gallons

column168: AFTER HOOKING UP HOSES TO TRAILER OUTLET AND PRESSURIZING TRAILER TO OFF LOAD, THE INTERNAL VALVE WAS OPENED AND THEN THE EXTERNAL VALVE WAS OPENED AND PRODUCT BEGAN TO LEAK AROUND THE C-CLAMP HOLDING THE EXTERNAL VALVE. UNLOADING PROCESS WAS STOPED AND CLAMP WAS TIGHTENED.
WHILE UNLOADING TRAILER #53-6177, FORK ON FORKLIFT PUNCTURED DRUM. DRUM WAS UP RIGHTED ASAP. MATERIAL THICK, LOOSING INLY APPROXIMATELY ONE-HALF GALLON.
ONE 55 GALLON DRUM PUNCTURED BY FORK LIFT TINE. INCIDENT CAUGHT IMMEDIATELY, ONLY LOSS LESS THAN ONE GALLON.

WHILE IN ROUTE TO MAKE A DELIVERY HE MAIN LOAD PIPE VALVE VIBRATED OPEN. THE SEAL ON THE CAP AT THE END OF THE LOAD PIPE WAS CRACKED, WHICH ALLOWED THE CAP TO LEAK. THE VALVE WAS CLOSED, A NEW SEAL INSTALLED IN THE CAP AND THE VEHICLE PROCEEDED ON TO MAKE ITS DELIVERY. BECAUSE OF THE SIZE AND WEIGHT OF THE ROUND HANDLE ON THE LOAD VALVE, VIBRATION WHILE TRAVELING CAN START THE HANDLE IN MOTION, THEREBY OPENING THE VALVE. TO STOP THIS MOTION A BRACKET WAS INSTALLED WITH A STRAP WHICH IS CONNECTED TO THE HANDLE. THE TENSION FROM THIS STRAP KEEPS THE VALVE CLOSED. THE DRIVERS WERE ALSO INSTRUCTED ON HOW TO INSPECT THE CAP AND REPLACE THE SEAL WHEN NEEDED.

column42: PRINTING INK, FLAMMABLE OR PRINTING INK RELATED MATERIAL (INCLUDING PRINTING INK THINNING OR REDUCING COMPOUND), FLAMMABLE
column168: WHEN THIS SHIPMENT ARRIVED AT HUB, ONE OF THE PIECES WAS FOUND TO HAVE ITS OUTER PACKAGING TOTALLY RIPPED APART. NONE OF THE INNER PACKAGINGS WERE DAMAGED. THE DAMAGED PIECE WAS PLACED IN A CONTAINMENT DRUM AWAITING DISPOSITION.

WHEN THIS SHIPMENT ARRIVED IN THE BUILD-UP AREA, ONE OF THE BOXES ON TOP OF THE OVERPACK WAS FOUND TO HAVE BEEN STABBED BY A FORKLIFT. THE FORKLIFT BLADE HAD DAMAGED THE TOPS OF TWO OF THE INNER PACKAGINGS, CAUSING A SMALL AMOUNT OF FLUID TO LEAK ONTO THE TOPS OF THE INNER PACKAGINGS. THE DAMAGED PIECE WAS REMOVED FROM THE OVERPACK AND PLACED IN A CONTAINMENT DRUM AWAITING WRITTEN AUTHORIZATION FOR DISPOSAL.

column42: FIRE EXTINGUISHERS CONTAINING COMPRESSED OR LIQUEFIED GAS
column168: ONE PIECE OF THIS SHIPMENT FELL TO THE GROUND FROM THE AIRCRAFT PALLET UPON WHICH IT WAS BUILT. THE EXTINGUISHER'S BOTTOM STRUCK THE GROUND, CAUSING A SMALL AMOUNT OF POWDER TO BE EXPELLED INTO AND OUT OF THE OUTER PACKAGING. THE DAMAGED PIECE WAS PLACED IN A CONTAINMENT DRUM AWAITING AUTHORIZATION FOR DISPOSAL.

AN EDWARDS OIL CO TANK TRUCK DRIVER WAS OFF LOADING FUEL OIL FROM HIS TANK TRUCK TO AN ABOVE-GROUND FUEL OIL STORAGE TANK. BECAUSE THE HIGH-LEVEL LIGHTS AND ALARMS ON THE STORAGE TANK WERE NOT OPERATING PROPERLY, THERE WAS AN OVERFILL, CAUSING A SPILLAGE OF 5-8 GALLONS OF FUEL OIL INTO THE CONCRETE CONTAINMENT AREA SURROUNDING THE STORAGE TANK. THE SPILL WAS SOAKED UP WITH PADS AND THE STORAGE TANK WAS WIPED FREE OF OIL. ALL CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE THEN PLACED INTO AN APPROPRIATE STORAGE CONTAINER FOR DISPOSAL BY NATIONAL STEEL PALLET CO. (THE OWNER OF THE STORAGE TANK) NATIONAL STEEL WAS NOTIFIED OF THE SPILL A-D INFORMED OF THE FAULTY ALARM EQUIPMENT ON ITS STORAGE TANK, SO THAT IMMEDIATE REPAIRS COULD BE MADE.

SHIPPER ADVISES THAT SUPERIOR CGA670 ALUMINUM/SILICONE/BRONZE VALVES ARE BEING REPLACED WITH AN IMPROVED DESIGN.

PACKAGE WAS PICKED UP BY DRIVER SCHERING PLOUGH AND BROUGHT OVER TO HAZ AREA FOR INSPECTION.  I INSPECTED PACKAGE AND COMPLETED PNF.  AS I LIFTED PACKAGE, I LIFTED IT ON ITS SIDE.  A LIQUID LEAKED OUT OF THE BOTTOM AND MIST CAME FROM THE SIDES AND CONDENSED ON OUTSIDE OF BOX.  PACKAGE WAS IMMEDIATELY ISOLATED OUT OF DOORS AND EMERGENCY RESPONSE WAS CALLED.

DRIVER CLAIMS THAT WHEN HE STUCK THIS UNDERGROUND TANK TO DETERMINE IF THE LOAD WOULD FIT, THE CUSTOMER SAID THAT THE TANK CHART OUR DRIVER WAS USING WAS WRONG AND THAT THE WHOLE LOAD WOULD FIT ACCORDING TO THEIR VEEDOR ROOT. THIS TANK HAS A 4" OPENING THAT THE DRIVER WAS USING TO DROP PRODUCT AND A 3" OPENING AT THE OTHER END OF THE TANK.W HEN APPROXIMATELY 6900 GALLONS WAS DELIVERED, THE CAP AT THE OTHER END OF THE TANK BLEW OFF. OUR DRIVER IMMEDIATELY SHUT DOWN THE PRODUCT FLOW BUT PRESSURE FROM THE TANK CAUSED APPROXIMATELY 50 GALLONS TO COME OUT OF THE 3" HOLE. MOST OF THE PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED ON THE CONCRETE PAD. THE SPILL WAS PROPERLY CLEANED UP BY AN AUTHORIZED ENVIRONMENTAL COMPANY AND PROPERLY DISPOSED OF.

THE DRIVER WAS DOING A ROUTINE INSPECTION PRIOR TO LEAVING A TRUCK STOP. SHE NOTICED THAT THE MATERIAL SHE WAS TRANSPORTING WAS LEAKING. THE SUBSTANCE HAD LEAKED NEAR THE DOORS BUT NOT ONTO THE GROUND. THE SHIPPER, MONSANTO, WAS CONTACTED AND THEY CONTRACTED C.E.T. OUT OF MOBIL, ALABAMA TO RESPOND. UPON OPENING THE DOORS, C.E.T. FOUND THAT A PALLET HAD BROKEN. THE BROKEN PALLET HAD CAUSED 2 DRUMS TO OVERTURN. ON CLOSER INSPECTION IT WAS DETERMINED THAT ONLY ONE DRUM HAD LEAKED. THE CAUSE OF THE LEAK APPEARS TO BE A BUNG THAT WAS NOT TIGHTENED PROPERLY AND HAD CAME LOOSE WHEN THE DRUM OVERTURNED. C.E.T. UP RIGHTED THE DRUMS, CLEANED AND OVERPACKED THE SPILLED MATERIAL AND CHECKED THE REMAINING DRUMS TO INSURE THAT THE BUNGS WERE PROPERLY SECURED. THE LOAD WAS THEN RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER.

column168: I NOTIFIED BY TELEPHONE AT 5:26 PM AN N&M TRANSFER DRIVER THAT A 55 GALLON DRUM OF A METHANOL BLEND HAD RUPTURED IN HIS TRAILER.  THE DRIVER INFORMED ME OF THE FOLLOWING: THE SHIPMENT HAD BEEN PICKED UP AT MESABA AIRLINES, AT THE HOUGHTON COUNTY MENOMINEE AIRPORT IN CALUMENT, MICHIGAN (UPPER PENINSULA OF MI ) .  HE SAID UPON ARRIVAL HE WAS SHOWN THE DRUMS AND ENDED UP REFUSING FOUR OF THE SEVEN DRUMS BEING OFFERED BECAUSE OF RESIDUE ON THE EXTERIORS.  THE DRUMS THAT WERE ACCEPTED WERE 55 GALLON PLASTIC, CONTAINING FLAMMABLE LIQUID.  OUR DRIVER WAS TOLD THAT THE DRUMS HAD BEEN SITTING IN STORAGE AT THE SHIPPERS FACILITY FOR SEVEN TO EIGHT YEARS LONG TIME. OUR DRIVER CALLED ME FROM MINOCQUA , WISCONSIN AT OUR TRAILER INTERCHANGE LOCATION.  ( THE TRAILER WAS TO BE PARKED THERE FOR THE REMAINDER OF THE EVENING.)  HE STATED THAT WHEN HE OPENED THE DOORS TO GET HIS TWO WHEELER HE NOTICED BY THE WET FLOOR THAT A RUPTURE HAD TAKEN PLACE.  THE THREE DRUMS IN THIS SHIPMENT WERE LOADED  IN THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER WITH A TWO PILES OF EMPTY SKIDS IN BEHIND THEM.  THE ONLY FREIGHT BEHIND THE EMPTY SKIDS WAS 20 LOOSE CARTONS OF SHOES.  ONE OF THESE DRUMS RUPTURED ABOUT 4" FROM THE BOTTOM.  THE CRACK WAS SHAPED LIKE A STAIR WAY.  WE HAVE NOT BEEN ABLE TO DETERMINE WHY THE DRUMS RUPTURED.  ALL DRUMS WERE FOUND TO BE UPRIGHT AND SECURED WHEN THE LEAK WAS DISCOVERED.  THE PALLETS WERE ALSO ALL IN PLACE.  I CONTACTED CHEM-TREC TO OBTAIN AN MSDS BUT THEY WERE NOT ABLE TO HELP.  CHEMTREC EVENTUALLY REACHED THE SHIPPER BY PHONE AND WE WERE THEN ABLE TO OBTAIN A DATA SHEET FROM THEM BY FAX.  OVER THE NEXT 90 MINUTES WE DETERMINED THAT INHALATION WOULD NOT BE HAZARDOUS AFTER VENTING THE TRAILER. EMERGENCY SPILL KITS AT THE TRAILER INTERCHANGE POINT WERE USED TO ABSORB THE SPILLED MATERIAL.  BECAUSE OF THE FLUID LIKE MAKE UP OF THIS MATERIAL IT WAS MOSTLY ABSORBED IN TO THE WOODEN TRAILER FLOOR.  VIRTUALLY NO MATERIAL HIT GROUND SURFACE. THE EXTERIOR OF THE TRAILER WAS CHECKED FOR MATERIAL AND WHEN DETERMINED SAFE THE TRAILER WAS RUN TO NEENAH , WISCONSIN HUB TERMINAL WHERE WE DISPATCHED IT TO A LOCAL TANK WASH FACILITY FOR DECONTAMINATION. COMMENTS 1) SHIPPER WAS NOT REGISTERED WITH CHEM-TREC  2) SHIPPER OFFERED CONTAINERS THAT DID NOT MEET UN PERFORMANCE PACKAGING STANDARDS. IT IS OUR CONTENTION THAT THE DRUM RUPTURED DUE TO AGE AND POSSIBLY EXPOSURE TO COLD WEATHER.

LOCAL EMERGENCY RESPONDERS AND ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTOR WERE NOTIFIED WITHIN ONE HOUR. CHEMTREE WAS NOTIFIED AT 1320 HOURS-IMMEDIATELY AFTER AN ASSESSMENT WAS MADE OF THE SITUATION. OTHER APPLICABLE REGULATOR AGENCIES WERE NOTIFIED AS FOLLOWS: REGION 2 (FRA, WASHINGTON, DC-NTSP-PENNSYLVANIA EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT AGENCY-PA,PUC-EPA AND THE NRC. CONTAMINATED SOIL WAS REMOVED FROM THE SCENE BY PETRO-CLEAN, AN ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTOR. SOIL CONTAMINATION WAS MINIMAL. CAR WAS UP RIGHTED AND SHIPPED ON TO ORIGINAL DESTINATION FOR UNLOADING. A WAIVER WAS GRANTED BY THE FRA TO MOVE THE DAMAGED CAR.

column168: FEDEX EMPLOYEE MARK ZAKROWSKI WAS UNLOADING THE PACKAGE FROM HIS TRUCK WHEN HE SAW UNDETERMINED LIQUID ESCAPE FROM THE BOTTOM OF THE BOX. THIS MATERIAL SPILLED ON THE TOE OF HIS BOOTS AND POSSIBLY ON HIS HAND WHERE HE HAD AN OPEN CUT. THE MATERIAL WAS BLEACHED AND SUBSEQUENTLY PLACED IN  A SALVAGE DRUM. I IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED THE CDC IN ATLANTA AND SPOKE TO DR. MATTHEWS. WE DON'T BELIEVE ANY FEDEX EMPLOYEE SUFFERED AN EXPOSURE AS DEFINED BY OSHA. HOWEVER MARK ZAKROWSKI WAS VISIBLY SHAKEN AS A RESULT OF THIS EXPERIENCE, HE SUBSEQUENTLY SOUGHT MEDICAL ATTENTION AND COUNSELING AT A LOCAL HOSPITAL. THERE HE HAD A BLOOD TEST TAKEN, THE RESULTS OF WHICH WILL NOT BE AVAILABLE IMMEDIATELY. AS THIS PACKAGE  APPEARED TO BE PROPERLY TENDERED IT WAS INSPECTED AND ACCEPTED BY FEDEX. IT WAS NOT UNTIL IT BEGAN TO LEAK THAT I KNEW WE WERE DEALING WITH A DISCREPANCY. THIS TYPE OF PACKAGING MUST HAVE ENOUGH ABSORBANT MATERIAL TO PRECLUDE ANY TYPE OF ACTUAL SPILL. HENCE, SINCE THIS PACKAGE ONLY HAD A DECLARED AMOUNT OF 20 ML (67% OF ONE OUNCE) AND STILL LEAKED I FELT WE NEEDED TO NOTIFY THE FAA. I SPOKE WITH FAA SPECIAL AGENT TONY ORTIZ. THE FREIGHT IS BEING HELD AT THE FEDEX STL RAMP PENDING AN FAA INSPECTION. IN ADDITION, I ATTEMPTED TO USE THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE PHONE NUMBER LISTED ON THE SHIPPING PAPER. I CALLED (213) 669-5610. THE NUMBER WAS MIRIAD OF VOICE MAILS. BASED ON THIS COUPLED WITH THE PACKAGING ASPECT THE FAA WAS NOTIFIED.

DURING THE SORT THIS BOX WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING AND EMITTING A VERY STRONG ODOR. THE BOX AND SPILLED MATERIAL WERE RECOVERED AND PLACED IN A SALVAGE DRUM. THE FREIGHT IS BEING RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER AT THEIR REQUEST.

THE MSDS REVEALED THAT THE FLASH POINT IS 53 DEGREES F. THE FAA WAS NOTIFIED. WE ARE HOLDING THE FREIGHT PENDING AN FAA INSPECTION AND DISPOSITION, THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELING, SHIPPING PAPERS OR OTHER INDICATORS THAT WOULD HAVE ALLOWED US TO READILY IDENTIFY THE CONTENTS AS BEING REGULATED BY THE U.S. DEPARTMENT OF TRANSPORTATION.

ON JANUARY 21, 1998, REPAIRS WERE MADE BY RESCAR, WHO TIGHTENED THREE (3)  OF THREE (3) SECUREMENT BOLTS ON THE SAFETY VENT ASSEMBLY AND CLEANED THE SPILL. column168: OUR VEHICLE ROLLED OVER AS IT TURNED THROUGH THE INTERSECTION FROM HIGHWAY 411 TO HIGHWAY 77.  THE RIGHT FORWARD SECTION OF THE TRAILER STRUCK THE CUB AS THE TRAILER SLID FORWARD.  THIS RESULTED IN A SMALL CRACK IN THE WELD BETWEEN THE HEAD AND THE BARREL OF THE TANK.  APPROXIMATELY 100 GALLONS OF PRODUCT LEAKED FROM THIS CRACK AND FROM THE CHRISTMAS TREE ON THE DOME LID.  EMERGENCY PERSONNEL BUILT A DIKE AROUND THE SPILL AREA TO PREVENT ANY FURTHER CONTAMINATION.  EMERGENCY RESPONSE SPECIALISTS WAS CALLED TO PROVIDE CLEANUP SERVICES.  ALL CONTAMINATED SAND WAS LOADED INTO ROLLOFF BOXES AND DISPOSED OF BY ALABAMA WASTE SERVICES AT THEIR FACILITY AT 3301 ACMAR ROAD, MOODY , ALABAMA.  A STORM DRAIN WAS DAMMED, AND ALL REMAINING PRODUCT WAS WASHED INTO A CARGO TANK PROVIDED BY MARTIN TRANSPORT.  THIS LIQUID WAS TAKEN TO INLAND CONTAINER IN ROME, GEORGIA WERE THE PRODUCT WAS RECOVERED AND THE WATER WAS TREATED.  NO INJURIES WERE SUSTAINED AS A RESULT OF THE HAZARDOUS SUBSTANCE. HOWEVER, THE DRIVER WAS HOSPITALIZED DUE TO A FRACTURED PELVIS SUFFERED FROM THE ROLLOVER.

NO OTHER INSTRUCTIONS WERE GIVEN TO OUR DRIVER. AT 1230 (CST) ON 1/26/98, SECURITY MANAGER OF ASSOCIATED GROCERS, CALLED OUR OFFICE IN WINONA, MN, NOTIFYING US THAT THEY BEGUN CLEAN UP PROCEDURES IN SEATTLE AT APPROXIMATELY 1345 ON 1/25/98, AND THAT THEY WERE STILL IN PROGRESS ON MONDAY, 1/26/98.

IT WAS DETERMINED THAT A HOLE IN SUMP CAUSED BY LIQUID PIPE RETAINER SPIDER DISENGAGED FROM BOTTOM OF PIPE ALLOWING BOTTOM OF PIPE TO RUB AGAINST RUBBER LINING IN SUMP CAUSING DEFECT IN LINING PERMITTING PRODUCT RESIDUE TO CONTACT SUMP. DURING THE DAY SHIFT ON JANUARY 20, 1997, BUILDING R-11 (R-11) PERSONNEL PREPARED A MONOMER MIX THAT REQUIRED A STYRENE CHARGE FROM THE STYRENE STORAGE TANK (NORMAL OPERATION) INTO THE R-11 MONOMER MIX TANK. ONE OF THE VALVES CONNECTING THE STYRENE STORAGE TANK TO THE MONOMER MIX TANK IN R-11 WAS NOT CLOSED AFTER THE STYRENE CHARGE. AT APPROXIMATELY 23:15, R-11 PERSONNEL, FROM A NEW SHIFT, PREPARED ANOTHER MONOMER MIX WHICH REQUIRED A SPECIAL SUPPLY OF STYRENE. THE REQUIRED STYRENE WAS TRANSFERRED DIRECTLY FROM THE SUPPLIER'S TANK WAGON INTO THE MONOMER MIX TANK IN R-11 USING THE STYRENE STORAGE TANK PUMP. DUE TO AN EMERGENCY IN THE PLANT, THE R-11 WORKER MAKING THE TRANSFER FROM THE TANK WAGON TO THE R-11 MONOMER MIX TANK WAS CALLED AWAY. THE DEPARTING WORKER NOTIFIED THE R-11 CONTROL ROOM OPERATOR THAT HE NEEDED TO LEAVE TO ATTEND TO THE EMERGENCY. AT APPROXIMATELY 00:10 (JANUARY 21, 1997), ANOTHER R-11 OPERATOR WENT OUTSIDE OF R-11 TO STOP THE TRANSFER FROM THE STYRENE TANK WAGON. THE OPERATOR OBSERVED A SMALL AMOUNT OF STYRENE COMING DOWN THE SIDE OF THE TANK WAGON, INFORMED THE R-11 SHIFT FOREMAN AND CLEANED UP THE STYRENE THAT WAS UNDER THE TANK WAGON (5 TO 10 GALLONS WAS THE ESTIMATE). THE OPERATOR AND THE SHIFT FOREMAN DID NOT OBSERVE STYRENE ENTERING THE CHEMICAL SEWER. AT APPROXIMATELY 07:45, THE PHILADELPHIA WATER DEPARTMENT (PWD) ARRIVED AT THE PLANT BECAUSE OF HIGH STYRENE READINGS AT THE POTW. THE PWD REPRESENTATIVE SAMPLED THE NEUTRALIZATION MIX TANK AND FOUND AN 8 INCH LAYER OF STYRENE. AT THIS POIN THE PWD REPRESENTATIVE CONTACTED THE PLANT ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGER AND REQUESTED THE DISCHARGE BE SHUT OFF AND THE STYRENE PUMPED OUT OF THE NEUTRALIZATION MIX TANK. BY APPROXIMATELY 08:00, THE PLANT SHUT DOWN ALL PROCESSES TO MINIMIZE FLOW TO THE SEWER. THE PLANT ALSO STARTED TO REMOVE STYRENE FROM THE TOP OF THE NEUTRALIZATION MIX TANK INTO DRUMS. THE PLANT CONTINUED TO REMOVE STYRENE, WORKING THROUGHOUT THE DAY WITH PWD TO RESUSCITATE A LINE RUSH TO REMOVE ALL STYRENE IN THE SEWER LINES AND NEUTRALIZATION MIX TANK, WITH THE STYRENE LAYER BEING REMOVED TO DRUMS. AT APPROXIMATELY 21:00, THE PLANT CONTACTED THE PWD TO INFORM THEM THE STYRENE REMOVAL WAS COMPLETE. THE PWD RETURNED TO THE PLANT, INSPECTED THE NEUTRALIZATION MIX TANK, AND ALLOWED RESUMPTION OF NORMAL OPERATIONS IN THE PLANT. THE INCIDENT REVIEW INDICATED THAT THE PHYSICAL CAUSE WAS IMPROPER VALVE ALIGNMENT. ONE OF THE STYRENE STORAGE TANK VALVES WAS NOT CLOSED AFTER FINISHING THE PREPARATION OF THE MONOMER MIX ON JANUARY 20, 1997. SUBSEQUENTLY, A STYRENE TANK WAGON WAS CONNECTED TO THE STYRENE STORAGE TANK INTO THE STYRENE TANK WAGON. STYRENE FROM THE STORAGE TANK FLOWED INTO THE STYRENE TANK WAGON WHICH OVERFLOWED AND WAS RELEASED INTO THE CHEMICAL SEWER SYSTEM. THERE WERE INADEQUATE TURNOVER MEASURES TAKEN WHEN THE R-11 PERSONNEL MAKING THE STYRENE TANK WAGON TRANSFER WAS CALLED TO AN EMERGENCY. THE SIGNIFICANCE AND QUANTITY OF THE STYRENE RELEASE WERE NOT RECOGNIZED AND

DRIVER #1 WAS NOT AVAILABLE FOR A STATEMENT. VEHICLE #2 WAS  PULLING A 1984 HEIL TANK TRAVELER BEARING MISSOURI TRAILER REGISTRATION #908 ZJH, Y.I.N. 1HLA3A78GE7J52 584. AT THE TIME OF THE ACCIDENT, THE TRAILER CONTAINED APPROXIMATELY 8,000 GALLONS OF GASOLINE. AS A RESULT OF THE ACCIDENT, APPROXIMATELY 25-35 GALLONS OF GASOLINE WERE SPILLED. AT THE TIME OF THE ACCIDENT, A DENSE FOG REDUCED VISIBILITY TO APPROXMATELY 150-200 FEET. DRIVER #2 STATED, ," I PULLED UP TO STOP WAITED FOR 3 CARS. LOOK NORTH NO ONE IN SIGHT STARTED TO CROSS. VAN CAME OUT OF FOG NO VISIBLE LIGHTS AND SLID UNDER TRAILER. VAN APPEAR TO BE TRAVELING VERY FAST."

column168: DEAN C COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY JESSE CONTREARAS, MECHANICAL DEPARTMENT, COLTON, CALIFORNIA, REPORTING A TANK CAR LEAKING ON LIGHT RIP TRACK #276.  THE ABOVE TANK CAR WAS IN THE TRACK FOR REPAIRS, AND WHEN ADDITIONAL CARS WERE ADDED TO THE TRACK AND COUPLED INTO THE TANK CAR, IT WAS NOTED LEAKING PRODUCT FROM THE TOP PORTION OF THE CAR.  AS THE CAR WAS PLACARDED CORROSIVE, THE AREA WAS SECURED, WHICH EFFECTIVELY ISOLATED THE CAR PENDING INSPECTION.  MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE COLTON YARD, LOCATED THE TANK CAR, AND OBSERVED SEVERAL PRODUCT TRAILS ON THE SIDES OF THE CAR, DIRECTLY BELOW THE MANWAY.  A SMALL 2X3 FOOT GROUND AREA BELOW THE CAR HAD BEEN CONTAMINATED AS A RESULT OF THE RELEASE. INSPECTION OF THE GATX (261-53) TRI-VENT PORTAL NOTED THE ABSENCE OF A FRANGIBLE DISC.  THE SAFETY VENT, A STANDARD GATX TRI-VENT ASSEMBLY MOUNTED ADJACENT TO THE 12 INCH FILL HOLE, WAS DISASSEMBLED, AND A STAINLESS/TEFLON BS&B 100 POUND FRANGIBLE DISC INSTALLED.  THE SAFETY VENT WAS REASSEMBLED AND THE REMAINING VALVES AND FITTINGS INSPECTED, WHICH WERE FOUND TO BE SECURE.  THE CAR AND GROUND AREA WERE NEUTRALIZED, WITH THE CAR THEN RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT ONTO THE CONSIGNEE.  NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSES, AND THE SHIPPER FOR CORRECTIVE ACTION.

THESE ITEMS WERE BOTH UNDER PRESSURE AND CONTAINED IN METAL RECEPTACLES PACKED IN A CLOTH BAG. THIS SHIPMENT CONTAINED OTHER REGULATED HAZARDOUS MATERIALS THAT DID NOT LEAK, SEE THE ATTACHED LIST. THERE WAS NO ABSORBENT USED IN THIS SHIPMENT. THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELS OR HAZARDOUS MATERIAL CERTIFICATIONS TO INDICATE THAT THIS WAS A REGULATED MATERIAL.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS REPACKED IN A RECOVERY DRUM DUE TO THE LEAK AND ODOR. THE ONLY REASON FOUND FOR THE LEAKAGE WAS UNSECURED CLOSURES. THIS SHIPMENT IS BEING HELD UNDER LOCK AND KEY PENDING FAA INVESTIGATION.

column168: ON 1/2/98 LEAD HAZ MAT SORTER, LINDA BOWMAN REPORTED A UNIT LOAD DEVICE THAT WAS EMITTING AN ODOR AT THE HAZMAT SORT FACILITY OF ABX AIR, INC.  PART - TIME HAZARDOUS MATERIALS TECHNICIANS, MARTIN CLINE AND ALAN HENDERSON RESPONDED. UPON ARRIVAL THE UNIT LOAD DEVICE WAS ISOLATED.  PART-TIME TECHNICIAN CLINE DONNED AN ORGANIC VAPOR CARTRIDGE RESPIRATOR TO INVESTIGATE.  INSIDE HE FOUND A FIBERBOARD BOX THAT WAS EMITTING ITS ODOR.  INSIDE THIS FIBERBOARD BOX WAS ANOTHER FIBERBOARD BOX THAT CONTAINED FIVE GLASS RECEPTACLES.  ONE OF THESE GLASS RECEPTACLE WAS BROKEN.  THIS ALLOWED ITS CONTENTS TO LEAK.  THESE GLASS RECEPTACLES WERE DIVIDED BY CARDBOARD DIVIDERS.  THERE WAS NO ABSORBENT MATERIAL USED.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS PROPERLY MARKED, LABELED AND PROPER CERTIFICATION ACCOMPANIED.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM AND FORWARDED BACK TO THE SHIPPER.

AS THE BOX WAS UNLOADED WE FOUND ONE CORNER HAD TORN AWAY AT THE SEAM.  IT APPEARED THAT THE BOX COULD NOT WITHSTAND THE WEIGHT PACKED INTO IT.  TWO OF THE BOTTLES OF NAIL POLISH HAD BROKEN AND SPILLED.  THERE WAS NO ABSORBENT MATERIAL IN THE BOX.  I SPOKE WITH THE SHIPPER, ALEX AGEE.  ALEX ADVISED THAT PLASTIC PEANUTS INCLUDED IN THE BOX WERE FOR ABSORBENCY.  I ADVISED THAT PLASTIC PEANUTS MELT WHEN AN ALCOHOL OR PETROLEUM BASED SOLVENT COMES IN CONTACT WITH THEM.  UPON REALIZING WE HAD A HIDDEN DISCREPANCY, I NOTIFIED THE BALTIMORE FAA CASFU.  I SPOKE TO SPECIAL AGENT KEN HARWOOD.  SPECIAL AGENT BROWN FROM THE FAA INSPECTED THIS FREIGHT, THIS MORNING.  ONCE THE FREIGHT IS RELEASE WE WILL ASK THE RECIPIENT TO PICK UP THE INTACT SHIPMENT AND THE BROKEN PARCEL WILL BE RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER IN A SALVAGE DRUM.

THE BOX WAS DROPPED DURING THE SORT,  UPON IMPACT THE GLASS BOTTLES BROKE ALLOWING THE CONTENTS TO ESCAPE.  EACH BOTTLE HAS THE PROPER SHIPPING NAME CLEARLY MARKED ON EACH BOTTLE'S LABEL.  THE FAA WAS NOTIFIED AT THE MIA CASFO.  I LEFT A MESSAGE ON THEIR ANSWERING MACHINE.  THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELING, SHIPPING PAPERS NOR OTHER INDICATOR THAT WOULD HAVE ALLOWED US TO READILY IDENTIFY THE CONTENTS AS BEING REGULATED.  THE FREIGHT WILL BE DESTROYED AS WASTE ONCE IT IS RELEASED BY THE FAA.

AIC OBSERVED A CLEAR LIQUID THAT SPILLED ONTO BOTTOM OF THE PALLET, WHICH OVERFLOWED ONTO THE FLOORING OF THE AC UPPER DECK, NEXT TO POSITIONS #7 AND #8. (1700 HOURS) MR. BRENDAN CHADWICK (TRANSPACIFIC ASSOCIATES GSA FOR POLAR AIR) MET THE AIR CRAFT AND CONTACTED ALOHA CARGO (GARY JENKINS - CUSTOMER SERVICE AGENT) REGARDING THE SPILL.  BRENDAN PROCEEDED TO LOOK FOR CORRESPONDING AWB'S AND THE DANGEROUS GOODS DECLARATION IN THE DOCUMENT POUCH TO HELP IDENTIFY CONTENTS OF THE DG SPILL AND CALLED BACK AT 1740 WITH THE INFORMATION. (1745 HOURS)  GARY AT ALOHA CONTACTED AQ CARGO DIRECTOR (BERT TAKUSHI) AND ALOHA PROCEEDED TO CHECK "EMERGENCY RESPONSE GUIDE" AND ALSO CALL CHEMTREC FOR PROPER RESPONSE IN CLEAN- UP .  CHEMTREC PUT ALOHA IN CONTACT  WITH MANUFACTURER OF DG, "3M CORPORATION " TO SEND MSDS INFORMATION. (1815 HOURS) ALOHA TRIED CALLING UNITEK TO COME OUT AD ASSIST WITH CLEAN - UP,  AS AIC HANDLERS STOPPED OFF LOADING AIRCRAFT UNTIL SPILL WAS CLEANED.  NO ANSWER AT UNITEK, UNABLE TO REACH ANYONE. (1830 HOURS) ALOHA THEN PROCEEDED TO CALL 911 TO CONTACT THE "HONOLULU FIRE DEPT."  TO RESPOND TO THE SPILL FOR ASSISTANCE IN CONTAINMENT AND CLEAN UP. (1850 HOURS)  HFD ARRIVED (CRAIG KAGAWA AND FRANCES BUENO - ASSISTANT CHIEF)  WENT ON BOARD THE AIRCRAFT.  SPILL ON AIRCRAFT FLOORING CLEANED UP WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL (APPROXIMATELY 1 TO 2 QUARTS) (1850 HOURS) BERT ARRIVED AT POLAR AIRCRAFT TO MEET HFD. (1905 HOURS)ALOHA CARGO AGENTS (3X) CLEANED -UP REMAINDER OF LIQUID RESIN SPILL ON AIRCRAFT WITH ADDITIONAL ABSORBENT MATERIAL WITH CLEARANCE OF "OK" FROM HFD KAGAWA. LATEX GLOVES AND LEATHER GLOVES USED. (1915 HOURS) BERT CONTACTED ALOHA'S DIRECTOR - CONTACT SERVICES (RAY SPENCER) TO ADVISE OF INCIDENT.         (1930 HOURS) AIC PERSONNEL OFFLOAD PALLET NO. "PMC 3731PO" WHICH CONTAINED DAMAGED STEEL DRUM(S), AND ALOHA PERSONNEL ASSISTED WITH BREAKDOWN AND IDENTIFYING DAMAGED CARGO.  ALOHA TOOK THE SHIPMENT OF 8 STEEL DRUMS CONTAINING THE "RESIN SOLUTION " BACK TO THE ALOHA CARGO FACILITY TO STORE IN ISOLATED AREA.  ALOHA CLEANED ON PALLET.  AIC PROCEEDED TO REBUILD CARGO ON ANOTHER PALLET. (1945 HOURS) BERT CONTACTED ALOHA'S MAINTENANCE DIRECTOR (RALPH AKUTAGAWA) FOR MECHANIC'S ASSISTANCE IN DOING A THROUGH CLEAN-UP OF POLAR AC#859FT FLOOR AREA. (2000 HOURS) BERT CONTACTED AIC MANAGER (FRED SPENCER TO ADVISE  OF STATUS. (2030 HOURS) ALOHA MAINTENANCE SUPERVISOR (GLEN PERALTA) CAME BACK TO POLAR AIRCRAFT TO INSPECT AND CONDUCT CLEAN-UP OF RESIN RESIDUE ON AIRCRAFT FLOOR.

THIS SHIPMENT WAS REPACKED INTO A RECOVERY DRUM AND WILL BE RETURNED TO SHIPPER UPON RELEASE FROM THE FAA.  THE SHIPMENT IS BEING HELD IN THE HAZ MAT SECURITY CAGE.

column168: AT 5:24AM ON 1/21/98 DRIVER ARRIVED WITH CCX TRAILER AT PHILADELPHIA TERMINAL. WHEN HE WAS BACKING HIS TRAILER IN HE NOTICED THAT SOMETHING WAS LEAKING FROM REAR OF TRAILER. I REVIEWED THE BILL OF LADINGS FOR HAZARDOUS MATERIALS OR OTHER LIQUID SHIPMENTS. THIS WAS THE ONLY ONE THAT APPEARED TO HAVE LIQUID SUBSTANCES. I TOLD DRIVER TO BACK HIS TRAILER AGAINST DOCK AND I WOULD INVESTIGATE THE LEAK. AS I APPROACHED THE TRAILER YOU COULD SMELL THE KEROSENE. I PROCEEDED TO OPEN THE DOOR AND NOTICED THE KEROSENE ON THE LAST FIVE FEET OF THE TRAILER. I IMMEDIATELY CONTACTED OUR SAFETY SUPERVISOR AND HE INFORMED ME TO CALL CHEMTREC. I NOTIFIED CHEMTREC AND GAVE THEM ALL PERTINENT INFORMATION. CHEMTREC INFORMED ME TO CLEAN AND COLLECT THE SPILL WITH NON-COMBUSTIBLE MATERIAL. THE SPILL  WAS CLEANED UP AND CONSIGNEE WAS NOTIFIED THAT THE NOW EMPTY STEEL TANK WAS GOING TO BE DELIVERED TO THEM TODAY AND WHAT HAD HAPPENED. THEY AGREED TO ACCEPT THE 8 GALLON RECOVERY DRUM THAT CONTAINED THE OIL DRY AND THE SPILLED KEROSENE. THE VALVE ON THE STEEL TANK DID NOT HAVE A CAP OR ANY LOCKING DEVICE TO PREVENT THE LEVER FROM OPENING.

UNION PACIFIC EMPLOYEES REPORTED PRODUCT LEAKING FROM TANK CAR NATX 37787. MATERIAL WAS REPORTEDLY DRIPPING FROM THE VICINITY OF THE BOTTOM OUTLET AT A SLOW RATE. CAR WAS INSPECTED BY UPRR SPECIAL AGENT K.C. DECHANT, WHO NOTED PRODUCT COMING IN A STEADY STREAM FROM THE BOTTOM OF THE TANK. FURTHER INSPECTION DISCLOSED LEAK WAS EMANATING FROM THE LIQUID EDUCATION VALVE UNDER MODERATE PRESSURE, RUNNING DOWN THE SIDE OF THE CAR, AND THEN DRIPPING FROM THE BOTTOM. ESTIMATED RATE OF LEAKAGE WAS 1 GALLON PER MINUTE. DECHANT RELIEVED INTERNAL PRESSURE BY OPENING THE VACUUM RELIEF VALVE, WHICH RESULTED IN THE LEAK SUBSIDING COMPLETELY. INSPECTION OF THE LIQUID VALVE DISCLOSED THE VALVE WAS INSTALLED LESS THAN HAND TIGHT ON THE EDUCATION PIPE. THE VALVE WAS TIGHTENED 3/4 TURN BY HAND, THEN WRENCH TIGHT TO SECURE AGAINST FURTHER LEAKAGE. AMBIENT TEMPERATURE AT THE TIME OF THE INCIDENT WAS IN EXCESS OF 50 DEGREE F. THE LEAK WAS APPARENTLY THE RESULT OF AN INTERNAL PRESSURE BUILDUP ATTRIBUTABLE TO AMBIENT CONDITIONS, WHICH PUSHED PRODUCT UP THE EDUCATION PIPE TO THE VALVE INTERFACE, WHERE THE LOOSE VALVE ALLOWED MATERIAL TO ESCAPE THROUGH THE THREADED CONNECTION. TIME FRAME OF THE INCIDENT WOULD INDICATE A MAXIMUM LOSS OF 55 GALLONS MATERIAL, WHICH DID NOT POOL ON THE GROUND BENEATH THE RAIL CAR, AND RAPIDLY EVAPORATED.

MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, D.A. LOW WAS NOTIFIED BY THE CAR DEPARTMENT, THAT AN ODOR WAS NOTED COMING FROM TANK CAR LOCATED ON THE WEST RIP LEAD. INSPECTION REVEALED THAT GAUGING ROD VALVE WAS CRACKED OPEN AND PACKING GLAND WAS LESS THAN TOOL TIGHT. ALSO, GAUGING ROD PACKING GLAND PACKING NEEDS TO BE REPLACED. RMCC AND ALICE MARTIN, COASTAL CHEM, WERE NOTIFIED OF THE ABOVE EXCEPTIONS.

column168: DEAN C. COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY THE ICTF SECURITY FORCES, REPORTING A LEAKING CONTAINER. MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE ICTF TERMINAL AND LOCATED THE ABOVE 20 FOOT CONTAINER IN SECTION E805, STALL#284. A SMALL POOL OF LIQUID (LESS THAN 1 GALLON) WAS OBSERVED ON THE PAVEMENT BETWEEN THE REAR AXLES OF THE CHASSIS WHERE THE PRODUCT HAD DRIPPED THROUGH THE FLOORING OF THE CONTAINER. THE CONTAINER WAS DIAPERED AND MOVED TO THE CUSTOMS DOCK  FOR INSPECTION. THE LIQUID WAS ABSORBED FROM THE PAVEMENT AND THE WASTE MOVED TO THE CUSTOMS DOCK FOR TEMPORARY RETENTION. UPON REMOVING SEAL MONSANTO ANNISTON 980, AND OPENING THE REAR DOORS,OBSERVED THE CONTENTS TO BE 55 GALLON DRUMS, LOADED 4 EACH TO PALLETS, AND DOUBLE STACKED THROUGHOUT THE CONTAINER. THE DRUMS WERE NOT SECURED TO EACH OTHER OR TO THE PALLETS, AND THERE WAS NO VISIBLE BILEVEL SEPARATION BETWEEN THE PALLETS FROM THE UPPER TIER TO PREVENT CONTACT WITH THE DRUM HEADS OF THE FLOOR TIER. THIS IS NOT A RECOMMENDED PROTOCOL FOR THE LOADING OF DRUMS AND IS NOT AN APPROVED METHOD PER THE AAR BOE 6C FOR THE TRANSPORTATION OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS VIA THE RAIL. THE RESTRAINT SYSTEM CONSISTED OF TY PATCH MATERIAL, WITH DOUBLE STRIPS COVERING EACH TIER AT THE REAR OF THE LADING. IT WAS OBVIOUS THE ENTIRE LOAD HAD SHIFTED AGAINST THE REAR DOORS OF THE CONTAINER, WHICH WAS PREDICATED BY THE MISAPPLICATION OF THE TY PATCH. AS THE LADING CONSISTED OF 80 DRUMS, THE ROWS OF DRUMS CONSISTED OF A 4,4,4 PATTERN, FRONT TO REAR. BASED UPON THE MANUFACTURERS RECOMMENDATIONS, UTILIZING THE TY PATCH SYSTEM REQUIRES DOUBLE BAYING OF THE DRUMS IN EACH TIER IN ORDER TO NOT EXCEED THE TEST STRENGTH OF THE MATERIAL. THIS ALSO REQUIRES THE FINAL ROW OF DRUMS IN EACH BAY TO END WITH A 3 PATTERN IN ORDER FOR THE DRUMS TO PROPERLY NEST AND ALLOW FOR THE SECUREMENT OF THE TY PATCH, EFFECTIVELY REDUCING THE MAXIMUM NUMBER OF DRUMS TO 76 FOR A PROPER LOADING. UPON REMOVING THE TY PATCH MATERIAL, OBSERVED ONE DRUM, SECOND OUT FROM THE RIGHT SIDE, TOP TIER, THAT WAS SO FATIGUED FROM ABRADING THE REAR DOORS, THAT THE SIDEWALL SEEM OF THE DRUM WAS SMOOTH, AND DEEMED UNFIT FOR FURTHER MOVEMENT. THE DRUM DIRECTLY BELOW ON THE FLOOR TIER, WAS SLAO DAMAGED IN THE SAME MANNER, HOWEVER THE DAMAGED WAS CAUSED BY AN ADJACENT DRUM MOVING AND OVERLAPPING THE BOTTOM CHIME, ALLOWING CHIME CONTACT WITH THE SEAM THAT EVENTUALLY ABRADED THE SEEM TO THE POINT OF FAILURE. THE DRUM WAS REMOVED, PATCHED, AND PLACED INTO A OVERPACK FOR SECUREMENT. BASED UPON THE WEIGHT OF THE DRUM AND THE AMOUNT OF PRODUCT ON THE FLOOR OF THE CONTAINER, IT IS ESTIMATED THAT 2-3 GALLONS WAS RELEASED. UPON INSPECTING THE REMAINING DRUMS, 6 MORE FROM FLOOR TIER HAD SUSTAINED SUFFICIENT DAMAGE TO ALSO DEEM THEM UNFIT FOR FURTHER MOVEMENT. ALL WERE PLACED INTO OVER PACKS FOR SECUREMENT. THE CONTAINER WAS DECONTAMINATED PER THE MANUFACTURERS RECOMMENDATIONS, AND THE INSPECTED DRUMS WERE THEN RELOADED INTO THE ORIGINAL CONTAINER WITH THE PRO

AT 1130 HOURS FRIDAY 1/9/98, H.L. BART WAS CONTACTED BY BILL STREETY, MTO, ANGLETON RELATIVE A LEAKING TANK CAR AT ANGELTON YARD TRACK 17 LOCATED 6 CARS DEEP ON THE SOUTH END. column168: MYO PORT LAREDO NOTIFIED SPECIAL AGENT HAZMAT, R. MEZA THAT THERE WAS A TANK CAR WITH A STRONG ODOR IN TRACK 001. MEZA CONTACTED A LOCAL CONTRACTOR. CODE 3 INC. TO ASSIST. UPON ARRIVAL MEZA MET WITH CODE 3 (BOB GALVAN & JORGE VELA). A SITE SAFETY PLAN WAS INITIATED. IT WAS NOT DETERMINED AT THIS POINT WHERE THE UNPLEASANT ETHER-LIKE ODOR WAS COMING FROM MEZA INSTRUCTED CODE 3 TO MONITOR THE IMMEDIATE AREA ABOUT HALF WAY DOWN OR NEAR THE MIDDLE SECTION OF TRACK 001. A TRACK LIST SHOWED FOUR EMPTY LAST CONTAINED HAZARDOUS MATERIALS TANK CARS. THE MONITOR A MX251 (CGI) COMBUSTIBLE GAS INDICATOR DID NOT INDICATE A READING ON ANY OF THE TANK CARS. ON THE ADJACENT TRACK 002 TANK CAR CELX 011274 WAS INSPECTED AS WELL. THE MANWAY COVER BOLTS WERE DISCOVERED LOOSE AND WERE TIGHTENED. ALSO, REPLACED THE MANWAY GASKET WITH A GORE TEX GASKET. IT WAS NOTED THAT THE GASKET IN PLACE HAD A TWIST AND WAS CUT. ADDITIONAL MONITORING OF THE AREA AFTER REPLACING THE GASKET INDICATED NO READINGS. IT WAS LATER HEARD VIA RADIO COMMUNICATIONS THAT A UPRR CARMAN WAS CLAIMING EXPOSURE, EMT RESPONDED AND TRANSPORTED HIM TO A LOCAL HOSPITAL FOR TREATMENT. ABOUT 2000 HOURS. A UPRR CLAIM AGENT WHO HAD RESPONDED TO THE INCIDENT TO INVESTIGATE HAD ALSO BEEN EXPOSED REQUIRING MEDICAL ATTENTION.

column168: DEAN C. COOPER, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY THE DENVER RMCC REPORTING THE ABOVE TANK CAR LEAKING. MANAGER COOPER CONTACTED CAR FOREMAN, GEORGE GAXIOLA, CALEXICO, CALIFORNIA, WHO STATED HE HAD BEEN NOTIFIED BY THE US CUSTOMS SERVICE, THAT UPON THEIR INSPECTION OF THE CAR, A FAINT LPG ODOR WAS NOTED COMING FROM THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING AREA. THE CAR WAS BEING INTERCHANGED BACK AS AN EMPTY TO THE UNION PACIFIC FROM THE MEXICAN RAILROAD AT CELEXICO. CONTACT WAS MADE WITH THE ORIGINAL SHIPPER, CONOCO, WHO REFERRED TO THEIR CUSTOMER, CENTENNIAL, WHO REFERRED TO THEIR BROKER, MEYERS GROUP, WHO IDENTIFIED THE CONSIGNEE OF THE LOAD TO BE TEXAS GAS AND OIL, MEXICALLI, B.C. AS TG&O HAD EMPTIED THE CAR, CONTACT WAS MADE WITH THE MEXICALLI PLANT, AND THEY PROVIDED A PERSON TO INSPECT THE CAR AND PROPERLY SECURE THE LEAK. INSPECTION DEVELOPED THE PACKING GLAND ON THE GAGING DEVICE WAS LOOSE, ALLOWING A VAPOR BY ASS. THE PACKING GLAND WAS PROPERLY SECURED, WHICH STOPPED THE LEAK. THE REMAINING VALVES AND FITTINGS WERE ALSO INSPECTED, AND FOUND TO BE SURE. THE CAR WAS RELEASED FROM BAD ORDER STATUS AND MOVED ONTO  THE CONSIGNEE. DUE TO THE TYPE OF PRODUCT AND MINIMAL AMOUNT OF VAPOR RELEASED, NOTIFICATIONS WERE ONLY MADE TO THE SHIPPER FOR CORRECTIVE ACTION.

WHILE THE FREIGHT WAS BEING SORTED IT BEGAN TO GIVE OFF A STRONG PETROLEUM BASED ODOR. THE BOX REMOVED FROM THE SORT AND OPENED.  THE CONTENTS REVEALED TWO FUEL CONTROL UNITS.  I SPOKE TO THE SHIPPER WHO SAID HE THOUGH THAT THE UNITS HAD BEEN COMPLETELY PURGED.  THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELING, SHIPPING PAPERS NOR OTHER INDICATOR THAT WOULD HAVE ALLOWED US TO READILY IDENTIFY THE CONTENTS AS REGULATED BY THE US DEPARTMENT OF TRANSPORTATION.  THE FREIGHT WAS PLACED IN A SALVAGE DRUM AND IS AWAITING AN FAA INSPECTION.  I NOTIFIED THE WESTERN REGION FAA DUTY OFFICER AND WAS CONNECTED WITH THE FAA SPECIAL AGENT ROY MORALES.

THIS PACKAGE WAS FIRST NOTICED DUE TO STRONG ODOR DURING THE SORTING OF INBOUND PACKAGES FROM A TRUCK ARRIVING FROM OUR EWR FACILITY.  DUE TO THE STRONG ODOR ASSOCIATED WITH THIS SHIPMENT, IT WAS SEPARATED FROM THE OTHERS AND THE SPILL CLEANUP AGENT, KEVIN BURNS WAS NOTIFIED TO FURTHER INSPECT THIS PACKAGE. KEVIN CALLED THE SHIPPER TO INFORM OF THE DELAY AND TO REQUEST A MSDS TO IDENTIFY THIS COMMODITY.  WHEN KEVIN RECEIVED THE MSDS HE NOTICED ME OF THE SITUATION.  ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION PROVIDed, THIS SHIPMENT SHOULD HAVE BEEN DECLARED AS A DANGEROUS GOODS SHIPMENT.  I CONTACTED JOHNSON BROWN WITH THE BWI FAA AND HE WAS INVESTIGATED THIS SHIPMENT. PACKAGE IS STILL BEING HELD UNTIL INVESTIGATION IS COMPLETED.

UPON NOTIFICATION OF DISPATCHER, CALLS WERE MADE TO MILLINOCKET FIRE DEPARTMENT, MAINE DEP, AND NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER.  A CALL WAS PLACED TO REQUEST THE HAZ MAT TEAM FROM GENERAL ALUM IN SEARSPORT.  MESSRS. TARDIF AND STROUT OF THE BANGOR AND AROOSTOOK RAILROAD ARRIVED AT MILLINOCKET AT 2025. MET MALCOM CAMPBELL OF MILLINOCKET FIRE DEPT AND TOM VARNEY OF THE MAINE DEP. HAZMAT TEAM ARRIVED AT 2055 HOURS. APPROACHED CAR TO DO A SNIFF TEST, DETERMINED LITTLE OR NO THREAT TO MOUNT THE CAR.  CHECKED VARIOUS VALVES AND FITTINGS UNDER DOME, FOUND EVERYTHING TO BE OK.  FELT THERE MAY BE SOME MINOR VENTING FROM THE SAFETY VALVE.  MR VARNEY OF THE DEP REQUESTED THE BAR TO MOVE THE CAR BACK TO SEARSPORT AT EARLIEST POSSIBLE TIME.  CAR OWNER WOULD SEND TEAM IN FROM LIMA, OHIO TO INITIATE REPAIRS.  TANK CAR WAS MOVED TO NORTHERN MAINE JUNCTION THAT NIGHT AND TO SEARSPORT ON 1/23/98.

column168: ON 1/23/98 A SPILL WAS REPORTED AT ABX AIR, INC. 145 HUNTER DRIVE WILMINGTON, OH 45177.  THE SPILL WAS IN OUT SORT "K" BUILDING FACILITY.  PART TIME SPILL TECHNICIANS, MARTIN CLINE AND CAROLYN CORDREY RESPONDED.  UPON ARRIVAL THEY DISCOVERED A WET STYROFOAM BOX.  THERE WERE ORIENTATION ARROWS ON THE BOX.  UPON INSPECTION THEY FOUND THE BOX WAS NOT MARKED, LABELED AND THE PROPER HAZARDOUS MATERIALS CERTIFICATIONS DID NOT ACCOMPANY THIS SHIPMENT TO INDICATE THIS WAS A REGULATED MATERIAL.  THE INNER BOX CONTAINED 8 x GLASS RECEPTACLES OF HYDROCARBON CONTAMINATED SPOIL, 7 OF THESE WERE WRAPPED IN PLASTIC BUBBLE WRAP.  THERE WERE 2 GLASS RECEPTACLES THAT WERE BROKEN.  THIS SHIPMENT ALSO HAD 2 x 1 GALLON ZIP LOCK BAGS WITH WET ICE.  ALSO FOUND INSIDE THIS SHIPMENT WAS A MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET.  THE MATERIAL SAFETY DATA STATED THAT THIS WAS POSSIBLY "PETROLEUM CRUDE OIL", UN1267, CLASS 3".  TH ONLY THEORY WE HAVE FOR THIS SHIPMENT LEAKING WAS FAILURE OF THE BASIC PACKAGING MATERIAL.  THIS SHIPMENT IS BEING HELD PENDING INVESTIGATIONS OF THE FAA.

ON 1/30/98 A SPILL WAS REPORTED AT ABX AIR, INC.  THIS WAS IN OUR HAZMAT SORT FACILITY.PART TIME, SPILL TECHNICIAN, MARTIN CLINE AND MATTHEW GORSVENOR RESPONDED.  UPON ARRIVAL; THEY DISCOVERED A FIBERBOARD BOX EMITTING AN ODOR.  THE OUTER BOX WAS MARKED, LABELED, AND THE PROPER HAZARDOUS MATERIALS CERTIFICATIONS DID ACCOMPANY THIS SHIPMENT.  UPON INSPECTION OF THE INNER CONTENTS THEY DISCOVERED 72 GLASS RECEPTACLES X .63 LITERS.  1 OF THE GLASS RECEPTACLES LEAKED, .63 LITERS OF FLAMMABLE LI     QUID N.O.S. WAS LOST.  THE ONLY THEORY WE HAVE FOR THIS SHIPMENT LEAKING IS POSSIBLE HANDLING AND THE BASIC PACKAGING MATERIAL.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS REPACKED INTO A RECOVERY DRUM AND FORWARDED TO THE DESTINATION.

ON 1/24/98 A SPILL WAS REPORTED AT ABX AIR INC.  PART TIME SPILL TECHNICIANS, DONNA RESOR AND CHRIS CHAPPA RESPONDED.  UPON ARRIVAL THEY DISCOVERED A FIBERBOARD BOX EMITTING AN ODOR.  THE OUTER BOX WAS PROPERLY MARKED AND LABELED AND THE PROPER HAZARDOUS MATERIALS CERTIFICATIONS.  UPON INSPECTION OF THE INNER CONTENT THEY FOUND 10 VIALS OF RESIN SOLUTION, ONE OF WHICH LEAKED.  IT WAS ESTIMATED THAT APPROXIMATELY RUBBING AND FRICTION OF THE INNER CONTENTS.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS REPACKED INTO A RECOVERY DRUM AND FORWARDED ON TO THE DESTINATION.

ON 1/30/98 A SPILL WAS REPORTED AT ABX AIR INC.  THIS SPILL WAS IN ONE OF OUR AIRCRAFTS. PART TIME SPILL TECHNICIANS, MATTHEW GROSVENOR AND MARTIN CLINE RESPONDED/  UPON ARRIVAL THEY FOUND A FIBERBOARD BOX THAT APPEARED TO BE LEAKING. THE OUTER BOX WAS MARKED, LABELED AND THE PROPER HAZARDOUS MATERIALS CERTIFICATIONS DID ACCOMPANY THIS SHIPMENT. THIS SHIPMENT WAS REPACKED INTO A RECOVERY DRUM AND FORWARDED TO THE DESTINATION.

ON 1/29/98 A SPILL WAS REPORTED AT ABX AIR INC.  THE LOCATION OF THIS SPILL WAS OUR "8" BUILDING SORT FACILITY.  PART TIME SPILL TECHNICIAN, DONNA RESOR AND TAMMY FLORENCE RESPONDED.  UPON ARRIVAL THEY DISCOVERED A WET FIBERBOARD BOX EMITTING AN ODOR.  THE OUTER BOX WAS NOT MARKED OR LABELED TO INDICATE THAT THIS SHIPMENT CONTAINED A REGULATED HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  UPON INSPECTION OF THE INNER CONTENTS, THEY FOUND 1 GLASS RECEPTACLE WRAPPED IN BUBBLE WRAP AND PACKED IN PEANUTS. DURING INSPECTION THEY DISCOVERED THAT THE CLOSURE WAS LOOSE AND APPROXIMATELY 1 OUNCE OF THE PRODUCT (DIESEL FUEL) LEAKED.  THIS WAS A 22 OUNCE RECEPTACLE.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS REPACKED INTO A RECOVERY DRUM AND PLACED INTO THE SECURITY CAGE, PENDING FAA INVESTIGATION.

column168: WHILE ON A REGULAR PEDDLE RUN, DRIVER ROBERT FURBER WAS EXPERIENCING SEVERE FROST HEAVES ALONG ROUTE 25 IN WENTWORTH, NH. FURBER STOPPED TO INSPECT THE LOAD AND FOUND THAT THE SKID HAD COLLAPSED UNDER THE WEIGHT (2,420) OF THE 4 DRUMS IN THE SHIPMENT. ONE DRUM HAD BEEN PUNCTURED BY A NAIL FROM THE BROKEN SKID. FURBER REACTED QUICKLY TO ROLL THE DRUM SO THE PUNCTURED HOLE WAS UP PREVENTING FURTHER LEAKAGE. APPROXIMATELY ONE HALF GALLON HAD LEAKED FROM THE DRUM AND WAS CONTAINED IN THE TRAILER. FURBER THEN NOTIFIED ME. I NOTIFIED CHEMTREC, THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTACT ON THE BILL OF LADING. CHEMTREC CONTACTED TEXO, WHO SUPPLIED ME WITH MSDS SHEETS FOR THE SPILLED CHEMICAL. GREAT NORTHERN ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES OF BATH, NH, WAS CONTRACTED TO GO TO THE SITE AND EFFECT A CLEAN UP OF THE SPILLED CHEMICAL AND THE PUNCTURED DRUM. THE PUNCTURED DRUM WAS OVERPACKED AND WILL BE RETURNED TO TEXO PER THEIR REQUEST.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: ON JANUARY 27, 1998, AT APPROXIMATELY 7:00 AM, SERVICE TRANSPORT COMPANY (STC) DRIVER JAMES IRVIN PROCEEDED EAST ON GENOA RED BLUFF ROAD IN PASADENA, TX. AS IRVIN APPROACHED A SECTION OF ROAD THAT TURNED LEFT, HE WAS UNABLE TO CONTROL THE TRACTOR-TRAILER UNIT. THE UNIT LEFT THE ROADWAY AND ROLLED ONTO ITS RIGHT SIDE. THE DRIVER WAS OBSERVED BY MEDICAL PERSONNEL AND LATER RELEASED AT THE SCENE. POLICe, FIRE TRANSPORTER AND SHIPPER PERSONNEL RESPONSE TO THE INCIDENT. LESS THAN 2 GALLONS OF PRODUCT SPILLED. THE LOAD WAS TRANSFERRED TO ANOTHER CARGO TANK BEFORE BEING UP RIGHTED. CONTAMINATED SOIL WAS EXCAVATED AND PROPER DISPOSAL IS PENDING. THE DRIVER WAS CITED FOR FAILURE TO CONTROL SPEED.

column168: AT ABOUT 7:45 PM ON THURSDAY, JANUARY 22, 1998, AN EMPLOYEE WORKING IN THE PILOT PLANT SAW WHAT APPEARED TO BE AN EXCESSIVE AMOUNT OF STEAM VAPOR SURROUNDING THE PAA CAR WHICH WAS BEING MELTED.  HE CALLED THE REACTOR  DECK OPERATOR TO COME DOWN TO THE TRACK TO INVESTIGATE.  AS THEY APPROACHED THE RR TRACK THEY NOTICED MOLTEN PAA FLOWING OUT FORM THE TOP OF THE RAIL CAR.  THEY IMMEDIATELY RADIOED THE BLEND DECK OPERATOR TO STAND BY IF A PLANT WIDE EMERGENCY ALARM WOULD BE NECESSARY.  THE EMPLOYEE THEN SHUT OFF OF THE STEAM AND CLOSED THE MANUAL VALVE FORM THE RAIL CONTAINMENT TO THE ENVIRONMENTAL SUMP.  WHEN THE STEAM WAS SHUT OFF THE FLOW OF PAA DECREASED AND THEN CEASED ALMOST IMMEDIATELY.  THE EMPLOYEE WHO DISCOVERED THE INCIDENT ESTIMATED THAT 1500-2000 LBS OF MATERIAL HAD BEEN RELEASED FROM THE CAR. IMMEDIATELY DAVID JACK AND JOHN TURNER WERE CONTACTED AND THEY ATTEMPTED TO CONTACT PETE BARRY.  THEY DETERMINED THAT THE ACTION ALREADY TAKEN HAD MITIGATED THE RELEASE AND THAT NO FURTHER ACTION WAS NECESSARY UNTIL FRIDAY MORNING WHEN THE PAA COOLED AND SOLIDIFIED SO THAT IT COULD BE SHOVELED UP.  AN INCIDENT REPORT AND A FORMAL INCIDENT INVESTIGATION WAS CONDUCTED ON FRIDAY, JANUARY 23, 1998.

SHIPMENT WAS BEING PROCESSED DURING THE INBOUND PACKAGE SUNDAY SORT WHEN THE DAMAGE OCCURRED.  THE SHIPMENT WAS BEING MOVED ABOUT THE WAREHOUSE ON A FORKLIFT TO A SECONDARY LOCATION.  AFTER BEING MOVED, THE PACKAGE WAS RUN OVER BY ANOTHER VEHICLE IN THE WAREHOUSE.  THIS HAD THE EFFECT OF COMPROMISING THE PACKAGING AND ALLOWING THE ENTIRE CONTENTS OF THE PACKAGE TO BE RELEASED.  THE DAMAGED EMPTY UNIT WAS CONTAINED IN A SALVAGE DRUM. THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD PENDING NOTIFICATION OF THE SHIPPER/RECIPIENT FOR DISPOSITION.

LIBBY, SR, SPECIAL AGENT HAZARDOUS MATERIALS, SEATTLE, WA WAS ADVISED THAT CONTAINER TRLU 306394, LOADED IN STACKWELL SPC 513213, LOCATED IN YARD 1 TRACK 037 (RAMP 7) SEATTLE AND WAS LEAKING.  HE ARRIVE ON SCENE NOTING CONTAINER TRLU 306934 HELD IN THE AIR BY THE RAYCO PACKER, PRODUCT LYING ON THE RAILCAR AND GROUND, ESTIMATING 1 GALLON OR LESS. JEFF HALL AND HANK BYNAKER, AMERICAN PRESIDENT LINE, SEATTLE CONTRACTED WITH FOSS ENVIRONMENTAL TO CLEAN THE RAILCAR, GROUND, OVERPAC ANY LEAKING DRUMS AND DECONTAMINATE THE CONTAINER.  FURTHER APL NOTIFIED THE U.S. COAST GUARD, WHO IN TURN NOTIFIED THE SEATTLE FIRE DEPARTMENT, ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION AGENCY.  ALSO, THE FEDERAL RAILROAD ADMINISTRATION AND WASHINGTON STATE UTILITIES TRANSPORTATION COMMISSION WERE NOTIFIED.  CONTAINER TRLU 306934 WAS OPENED FOR INTERIOR INSPECTION, FINDING EVIDENCE OF A LIQUID LEAK IN THE LEFT NOSE CORNER 2ND TIER OF DRUMS.  THIS DRUM WAS BELIEVED TO HAVE BEEN STRUCK BY A FORKLIFT WHEN LOADING. HOWEVER, IT WAS LATER DETERMINED TO HAVE LOOSE BUNG.  IN ADDITION, EIGHT MORE DRUMS WERE FOUND TO BE LEAKING FROM THEIR BUNGS.  ON OF THESE ALSO WAS NOTED TO BE LEAKING AT THE BOTTOM WELD SEAM. ONE DRUM WAS NOTED LEAKING AT THE BOTTOM WELD SEAM ONLY.  FURTHER ANOTHER FOUR DRUMS WERE SEVERELY DENTED, HOWEVER NOT LEAKING.  ALL 14 DRUMS IN QUESTION WERE PLACED IN 85 GAL OVERPACK DRUMS AND ARE GEING TEMPORARILY STORED IN CONTAINER GSTU 510149, PENDING DISPOSITION.  A TOTAL OF  58 DRUMS WERE LOADED INTO CONTAINER GSTU 510149 AND FORWARDED TO CONSIGNEE.  THE ORIGINAL CONTAINER TRLU 306934 HAS BEEN DECONTAMINATED AND HAS HAD THE WOODEN FLOOR REMOVED AND IS BEING HELD PENDING FURTHER DISPOSITION FOR REPAIR OR DISPOSAL.

AT 1016 HRS 1/20/98 RECEIVED CALL FROM TED DONNER OF ENRON OPERATIONS CORP THAT THEY HAD A TANK CAR MOGX 1044 ON THEIR LOADING RACK WHICH WAS BEING LOADED WHEN THEY NOTICED A LEAK AT THE BOTTOM OF THE TANK.  ENRON REQUESTED ASSISTANCE FROM THE UPR CTS GROUP.  H. L. BART AND P. K. PERSON RESPONDED TO ENRON'S PLANT AND UPON ARRIVAL AT 1100HRS DISCOVERED CART TO HAVE BEEN COMPLETELY LOADED PROPER TO DISCOVERY OF THE LEAK BY LOADING PERSONNEL.  TANK CAR MOGX 1044 APPEARED TO HAVE A CRACK INBOARD OF THE STUB SILL ON THE B-END OF THE TANK.  ICE HAD FORMED ALONG THE LONGITUDINAL CENTER LINE OF THE TANK BOTTOM. VAPOR DISPERSION WAS EFFECTED USING TWO UNMANNED MONITORS AND 2 INCH HOSE LINES.  AND CAR MOGX 1044 WAS UNLOADED VIA A LIQUID FLARE. PRODUCT REMOVE AND TANKCAR PURGED WITH WATER TO REMOVE ALL VAPORS.  CAR IS TO BE ROUTED TO SHOP BY ENRON PERSONNEL INCIDENT TERMINATED AT 1900 HRS 1/20/97.

column168: DEAN C COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY MATT BATTLE, MANAGER, YARD OPERATIONS, EAST YARD LOS ANGELES, CA, WHO STATED THE CITY OF VERNON FIRE DEPARTMENT HAD CONTACTED HIM AND REPORTED THEY WERE ON SITE WITH A LEAKING TANK CAR. THE ABOVE TANK CAR WAS ON THE FRUITLAND PASS TRACK, CITY OF VERNON, AND WAS DRIPPING PRODUCT FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET.  MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE CITY OF VERNON, AND MET WITH THE BATTALION CHIEF FOR THE LOS ANGELES COUNTY FIRE DEPARTMENT, ALONG WITH THE BATTALION CHIEF FROM THE CITY OF VERNON FIRE DEPARTMENT. INSPECTION OF THE LEAKING TANK CAR DEVELOPED THE CAR WAS IN FACT LEAKING FROM THE EXTERIOR HEATER COIL CONNECTION ON THE "A" END OF THE CAR, ADJACENT TO THE BOTTOM OUTLET.  THE HEATER COIL HAD A CLOSURE CAP, HOWEVER, IT WAS LOOSE, ALLOWING PRODUCT TO BYPASS THE CLOSURE.  AS THE PRODUCT WAS ESCAPING FROM THE HEATER COIL LINE, IT WAS APPARENT THE INTERNAL LINE WAS DAMAGED.  THE AAR BUREAU OF EXPLOSIVES PAMPHLET 34 ADDRESSES THE HEATER COIL CLOSURES BE REMOVED DURING THE LOADING PROCESS IN ORDER TO DETECT THESE TYPES OF FAILURES.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT HAZ MAT TEAM MADE ENTRY AND UTILIZED A PIPE WRENCH TO PROPERLY SECURE THE HEATER COIL LINE CAP, WHICH STOPPED THE LEAK.  THE GROUND AREA BETWEEN THE TRACKS WAS SAMPLED, AND BASED UPON THE RETURN ANALYTICAL, THE AREA WILL BE CLEANED OF THE RESIDUE.  DUE TO THE TYPE OF COMMODITY AND THE MINIMAL AMOUNT RELEASED, NOTIFICATIONS WERE ONLY MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSES, AND THE SHIPPER FOR CORRECTIVE ACTION.

SPECIAL AGENT HAZARDOUS MATERIALS, ED FEDRICK RESPONDED TO A REPORT THAT TANK CAR DOWX 6834, IN THE ALDEN BRIDGE SIDING AT BENTON, LA.  WAS LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE.  HE WAS MET ON THE SCENE BY LA STATE HAZMAT TEAM, STEVE CHILDERS AND MIKE DEERE. THE CAR WAS A RESIDUE EMPTY AND LEAK WAS STOPPED BY TIGHTENING THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE. THE STATE HAZMAT TEAM ADVISED THAT THEY WOULD ADVISE THE SHIPPER BY LETTER.

column168: AB0399 SHIPPER: VIDENT, AWB# NOC 1948237824 CGO. THIS SHIPMENT WAS PROPERLY MARKED, LABELED AND CERTIFIED AS A REGULATED MATERIAL. 00:08, 01/28/98 AN ODOR WAS REPORTED IN BUILDING 207 OF OUR SORT FACILITY LOCATED AT: ABX AIR INC., 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON, OHIO 45177. PART TIME SPILL TECHNICIANS TIM HINES AND MARTIN CLINE DONNED NOMEX SUITE AND AIR PURIFYING RESPIRATORS WITH HEPS CARTRIDGES AND RESPONDED TO THE ODOR. UPON ARRIVAL THEY FOUND A BROWN FIBERBOARD BOX WITH VISIBLE SIGNS OF LEAKAGE ON THE TOP OF THE BOX. THE BOX WAS MARKED, LABELED AND CERTIFIED AS THE FOLLOWING REGULATED MATERIAL: ETHANOL SOLUTION, UN1170, LTD QTY. THEY OPENED THE BOX AND FOUND ONE PLASTIC CONTAINER WITH FRICTION TYPE CLOSURE. THE CLOSURE ON THE PLASTIC BOTTLE WAS BROKEN CAUSING THE LEAKAGE OF APPROXIMATELY 5 OUNCES OF THE ETHANOL SOLUTION. THE PLASTIC BOTTLE WAS ALSO LOADED INSIDE THE BOX AGAINST OUTER PACKAGE ORIENTATION ARROWS. THE PLASTIC BOTTLE WAS LOADED AT A 46 DEGREE ANGLE. THERE WAS INSUFFICIENT ROOM INSIDE THE BOX TO LOAD THE PLASTIC BOTTLE IN AN UPRIGHT POSITION. THE OUTER FIBERBOARD BOX ABSORBED ALL OF THE LEAKAGE. THEY RESEALED THE BOX, PLACED IT INSIDE 2 PLASTIC BAGS WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL. THE SHIPMENT WAS PLACED INSIDE A RECOVERY DRUM FOR TRANSPORT ON TO FINAL DESTINATION. ALL HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MARKINGS, LABELS AND CERTIFICATION WERE APPLIED TO THE OUTSIDE OF THE RECOVERY DRUM BEFORE THE SHIPMENT WAS TRANSPORTED. CLEAR OF SCENE: 03:20. THERE WERE A PACKING LIST ATTACHED TO THIS SHIPMENT. THE ITEMS LISTED ON THE PACKING LIST WERE NOT INCLUDED IN THIS SHIPMENT. THE PACKING LIST DOES NOT INCLUDE THE ETHANOL SOLUTION.
